---
import DocsLayout from "../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro";
import CodeTabs from "../../components/CodeTabs.astro";
---

<DocsLayout title="Introduction">
	<p class="lead">Multi-trigger inline mentions for React and Vue. Built on a framework-agnostic core.</p>

	<h2>What is @skyastrall/mentions?</h2>
	<p>A production-grade mentions input that supports <code>@users</code>, <code>#tags</code>, <code>/commands</code>, and custom triggers — each with its own data source, color, and configuration.</p>

	<p>It ships as a core engine and thin framework adapters:</p>
	<ul>
		<li><code>@skyastrall/mentions-core</code> — Framework-agnostic state machine, markup parser, trigger detection. ~9KB gzipped.</li>
		<li><code>@skyastrall/mentions-react</code> — React adapter with drop-in component, compound components, and headless hook. ~5KB.</li>
		<li><code>@skyastrall/mentions-vue</code> — Vue 3 adapter with composable and compound components. ~5KB.</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>Three API Layers</h2>
	<p>Pick the level of control you need:</p>

	<h3>1. Drop-in Component</h3>
	<p>One import, one component, works out of the box.</p>
	<CodeTabs
		react={`<Mentions
  triggers={[{ char: "@", data: users }]}
  onChange={(markup, plainText) => {}}
/>`}
		vue={`<Mentions
  :triggers="[{ char: '@', data: users }]"
  v-model="markup"
/>`}
	/>

	<h3>2. Compound Components</h3>
	<p>Control the layout. The library handles state, ARIA, and keyboard navigation.</p>
	<CodeTabs
		react={`<Mentions triggers={triggers}>
  <Mentions.Editor placeholder="Type @..." />
  <Mentions.Portal>
    <Mentions.List>
      <Mentions.Item render={({ item }) => <UserCard user={item} />} />
    </Mentions.List>
  </Mentions.Portal>
</Mentions>`}
		vue={`<Mentions :triggers="triggers">
  <MentionsEditor placeholder="Type @..." />
  <MentionsPortal>
    <MentionsList>
      <MentionsItem v-slot="{ item }">
        <UserCard :user="item" />
      </MentionsItem>
    </MentionsList>
  </MentionsPortal>
</Mentions>`}
	/>

	<h3>3. Headless Hook / Composable</h3>
	<p>Full control. You get props, state, and helpers — render whatever you want.</p>
	<CodeTabs
		react={`const { inputProps, listProps, getItemProps, editorRef, isOpen, items } =
  useMentions({ triggers });`}
		vue={`const { aria, editorRef, isOpen, items, handleInput, handleKeyDown } =
  useMentions({ triggers });`}
	/>

	<h2>Key Features</h2>
	<ul>
		<li>Multi-trigger support with per-trigger colors and data sources</li>
		<li>Framework-agnostic core — React and Vue adapters shipped, more coming</li>
		<li>Contenteditable with DOM-first architecture</li>
		<li>Ghost text for AI inline completions (Tab to accept)</li>
		<li>Async data with debounce, abort, and loading states</li>
		<li>Single-line mode with Enter/paste/drop prevention</li>
		<li>WAI-ARIA combobox pattern with keyboard navigation</li>
		<li>~9KB core + ~5KB adapter gzipped, zero runtime dependencies in core</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>Next Steps</h2>
	<p><a href="/docs/installation">Installation</a> or <a href="/docs/quick-start">Quick Start</a>.</p>
</DocsLayout>
